"""
MKT Christ Commentary — Acts chapters 16–17
Run: python3 scripts/zc-christ-acts-16-17.py

Christological focus for this range:
- The 'Spirit of Jesus' (16:7) — the only NT occurrence of this precise phrase —
  frames the entire Macedonian mission as Christ's own missionary initiative.
- The Philippian jailer scene (16:30-34) is the missionary gospel in miniature:
  'What must I do to be saved? Believe in the Lord Jesus.'
- Acts 17:3 is Paul's most compressed Christological thesis: 'the Messiah had to
  suffer and rise from the dead; this Jesus I am proclaiming to you is the Messiah.'
- The Areopagus speech (17:22-31) is the most sustained natural-theology argument
  in Acts, but it climaxes in the resurrection: every philosophical approach to
  God leads to the specific man God appointed as judge (v31).
- ch17 v31 already exists — merge_comm will preserve it.
- No straight double-quote characters in value strings (use curly quotes or escaped).
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(layer, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / layer / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(layer, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / layer / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    """Never overwrites existing entries — safe to re-run."""
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

CHRIST = {
  "16": {
    "1": "<p>Paul's arrival in Lystra and his discovery of Timothy introduces the man who will become his closest apostolic partner — 'my true son in the faith' (1 Tim 1:2). Timothy's mother is Jewish (Eunice, 2 Tim 1:5), his father Greek: he embodies the mixed heritage that the gospel is crossing. The Christological significance: Christ calls to himself those from every background, and then sends them back into the world as bridges between the communities they span. Timothy's bicultural identity will make him uniquely effective in the Pauline mission.</p>",

    "2": "<p>Timothy's good reputation among the Lystra and Iconium believers is the community's testimony to his character — a Christological criterion for ministry (1 Tim 3:7, 'he must also have a good reputation with outsiders'). The risen Christ builds his mission force not from those with the most impressive credentials but from those who have demonstrated faithfulness in the local community. Paul's pattern of identifying co-workers is the risen Christ's pattern of calling: he looks at the character being formed by the Spirit, not the résumé.</p>",

    "3": "<p>Paul circumcises Timothy not as a theological concession (Gal 2:3 — Titus was not circumcised) but as a missionary strategy: Timothy's Jewish mother makes him Jewish in Jewish eyes, and his lack of circumcision would close synagogue doors. The Christological principle: 'to the Jews I became as a Jew' (1 Cor 9:20) — Paul's missional flexibility embodies Christ's own incarnational logic of entering the world on its own terms. The Christ who became flesh (John 1:14) calls his missionaries to culturally appropriate self-limitation for the sake of others' reception of the gospel.</p>",

    "4": "<p>The delivery of the Jerusalem Council decisions — 'the decisions reached by the apostles and elders in Jerusalem' — is the apostolic community's authoritative teaching function, grounded in the Holy Spirit's guidance (15:28, 'it seemed good to the Holy Spirit and to us'). Christologically, the Council's decisions represent Christ's own ordering of his community through the Spirit: the risen Lord governs his church through shared discernment, not unilateral decree. The decisions about Gentile inclusion are expressions of the Christological reality that 'there is no distinction between Jew and Greek' (Rom 10:12).</p>",

    "5": "<p>The churches were strengthened in the faith and grew daily in numbers — a Christological summary that belongs with Acts 2:47 ('the Lord added to their number daily') and 6:7 ('the word of God spread'). Growth is the Spirit's work, not the apostles' achievement; the risen Christ adds to his church as he builds it (Matt 16:18, 'I will build my church'). The simultaneous strengthening (qualitative) and growth (quantitative) resist the false choice between depth and breadth in ecclesiology.</p>",

    "6": "<p>The Spirit's prohibition — having been kept by the Holy Spirit from preaching the word in the province of Asia — is one of the most striking examples of divine redirection in Acts. Asia would later receive the gospel (ch. 19), but not yet; Christ has a different destination in mind. The Christological point: the risen Lord directs his mission not by general permission but by specific guidance, holding some doors closed until the appointed time. Paul's obedience to the Spirit's restraint is as theologically important as his obedience to the Spirit's sending.</p>",

    "7": "<p>A direct revelation: 'The Spirit of Jesus would not allow them.' <em>Pneuma Iēsou</em> — 'Spirit of Jesus' — is the only occurrence of this exact phrase in the NT (elsewhere: Spirit of God, Holy Spirit, Spirit of Christ in Rom 8:9). Luke's unusual phrasing identifies the directing Spirit explicitly with the risen Jesus: the one who guides the Macedonian mission is the same Jesus who rose from the dead and ascended to the Father's right hand. The Pentecost promise (Jesus received the Spirit and poured him out, Acts 2:33) is here inverted: Jesus acts through the Spirit as his own Spirit. The Spirit of Jesus is Jesus acting in the age of the church.</p>",

    "8": "<p>Troas is not merely a transit point: it is where Paul will later raise Eutychus (20:7-12), and it was the launching pad for the gospel's crossing into Europe. The geographical precision — Mysia bypassed, Troas reached — reflects Luke's careful travel itinerary and the underlying Christological claim that every step of the mission is under divine guidance. The roadblocks (Asia closed, Bithynia closed) have funneled the mission to the coast, to the port that looks across the Aegean toward Macedonia.</p>",

    "9": "<p>The Macedonian vision — a man standing and begging, 'Come over to Macedonia and help us' — is the pivotal moment when the gospel crosses from Asia to Europe. Christologically, this is the Spirit of Jesus directing the expansion of the Servant's light to a new continent (Isa 49:6, 'to the ends of the earth'). The vision's structure — a human plea, a divine response, apostolic obedience — models the dynamic of the entire mission: human need reaches heaven, heaven sends the church, the church obeys and goes. The 'man of Macedonia' has been read as Luke himself (the 'we' sections begin at v10), inviting Paul to the community Luke knew.</p>",

    "10": "<p>The 'we' section begins: 'After Paul had seen the vision, we got ready at once to leave for Macedonia.' Luke joins the mission party, and his narrative presence gives Acts 16-28 the texture of firsthand witness. Christologically, the 'we' narrative is itself a Christological argument: the gospel that Luke now records was witnessed by him personally — the resurrection proclamation rests on the testimony of those who saw (1:22 — the apostolic criterion), and Luke is now one of the witnesses to the post-resurrection mission. The urgency ('at once') is obedience to the Spirit of Jesus.</p>",

    "11": "<p>The voyage from Troas to Philippi — Samothrace, Neapolis, Philippi — is described with the precision of a ship's log. Luke's nautical vocabulary throughout Acts 16-28 reflects firsthand experience. The Christological significance of the swift crossing (two days, compared to the five days it will take in the opposite direction, 20:6) is Luke's implicit note that the wind was with them — divine favour on the mission to Macedonia. The gospel's first crossing to Europe has divine wind in its sails.</p>",

    "12": "<p>Philippi, a Roman colony and the leading city of Macedonia, is the first European city where the gospel takes root. Christologically, Philippi is the beachhead for the gospel's advance to Rome itself: a Roman colony is a miniature Rome, governed by Roman law and populated by Roman citizens and veterans. The gospel that will eventually reach Rome (28:31) first touches Roman culture in this Macedonian city. The letter Paul will later write to the Philippians (Phil 1:27 — 'conduct yourselves in a manner worthy of the gospel of Christ') reflects his deep investment in this community of Roman citizens shaped by the crucified Lord.</p>",

    "13": "<p>The Sabbath gathering by the river — outside the city gate, at a place of prayer (<em>proseuché</em>, possibly a synagogue building, possibly an open-air gathering) — shows Paul's consistent pattern: go to the Jewish community first, because the Scriptures that point to Christ are already in their hands. The women gathered at the river form the first European congregation; Lydia's household will be the first European church. The river-side prayer meeting is where the gospel crosses from proclamation to community formation.</p>",

    "14": "<p>A direct revelation: 'The Lord opened her heart to respond to Paul's message.' Lydia's conversion is one of the most precise descriptions of the mechanics of grace in Acts: the initiative is entirely divine (<em>ho kyrios diēnoixen tēn kardian</em>), but it operates through Paul's speaking and Lydia's listening. The Lord who commanded light to shine out of darkness (2 Cor 4:6) here opens a heart that was already seeking him — she worshipped God before Paul arrived. Grace perfects seeking; it does not wait for passive neutrality. Lydia is the first named European convert, and she becomes the host of the first European church.</p>",

    "15": "<p>Lydia's household baptism and her immediate hospitality — 'if you consider me a believer in the Lord, come and stay at my home' — show the inseparability of faith, baptism, and community formation in the apostolic pattern. The Christological logic: those incorporated into Christ through baptism immediately become Christ's body for one another. Lydia's house becomes the base of operations for the Philippian mission — the same house to which Paul and Silas will return after the jail (v40). The church is where the Lord's people gather, and it begins in a businesswoman's home.</p>",

    "16": "<p>The slave girl with a 'spirit of divination' (<em>pneuma pythōna</em> — a spirit of the Pythian oracle, associated with the Delphic Apollo) correctly identifies Paul and Silas as servants of the Most High God who proclaim the way of salvation. The demonic confession is theologically accurate (cf. Mark 1:24 — the demon in the synagogue correctly identified Jesus); but Paul does not accept advertising from a demonic source. The Christological principle: the gospel does not need endorsement from unclean spirits, even accurate ones. Truth proclaimed from a corrupt source corrupts the truth's reception.</p>",

    "17": "<p>The spirit's proclamation — 'these men are servants of the Most High God, who are telling you the way to be saved' — is an involuntary Christological confession. <em>Theos Hypsistos</em> (Most High God) is used in the LXX for YHWH (Gen 14:18; Num 24:16; Ps 7:17) and in the broader Greco-Roman world for the supreme deity. The spirit knows the mission's true character, even if its owners do not. The Christological content of the proclamation — 'the way to be saved' (<em>hodon sōtērias</em>) — is the gospel of the Messiah's death and resurrection, which is the only way to salvation (Acts 4:12).</p>",

    "18": "<p>A direct revelation: Paul commands the spirit 'in the name of Jesus Christ' to come out — and it comes out at once. The exorcism formula '<em>en onomati Iēsou Christou</em>' places the authority entirely with the risen Lord: Paul is not exercising personal spiritual power but acting as Christ's representative in Christ's name. This is the same formula Peter used (3:6 — 'in the name of Jesus Christ of Nazareth, walk') and the apostles used throughout Acts. The name of Jesus is the authority under which the apostolic mission operates; its power over demons demonstrates that Christ has indeed disarmed the powers (Col 2:15).</p>",

    "19": "<p>The owners' anger is economic: 'their hope of making money was gone.' The gospel repeatedly destroys commercial exploitation of spiritual power — here slave-based divination; earlier, Simon's sorcery (8:18-20); later, Demetrius's idol trade (19:23-27). The Christological pattern: where Christ's name is genuinely operative, the economic structures built on spiritual exploitation collapse. The owners drag Paul and Silas to the magistrates — the first of Paul's many Roman trials. Christ, through his apostles, will repeatedly confront the political-economic systems that exploit human beings for profit.</p>",

    "20": "<p>The charge before the magistrates — 'these men are Jews, and are throwing our city into an uproar by advocating customs unlawful for us Romans to accept or practise' — is the first formal legal accusation against the gospel in a Roman civic context. The charge is civic disorder + foreign customs; both are standard Roman pretexts for suppression of new religious movements. The Christological irony: the gospel that proclaims the true ruler of the world (17:7 — 'there is another king, Jesus') is accused of subverting Roman civic order. The accusation is both false (the gospel creates community, not riots) and partially accurate (the gospel does claim a king above Caesar).</p>",

    "21": "<p>The specific charge of advocating 'customs unlawful for us Romans to accept or practise' targets the exclusive claims of the gospel. Roman religion was syncretic — all gods were welcome, as long as the emperor cult was also honoured. The Christological claim that 'there is no other name under heaven by which we must be saved' (4:12) was the non-negotiable at every point of friction between the gospel and Roman pluralism. Paul is not proclaiming a private spirituality that can coexist peacefully with all other religions; he is proclaiming a Lord who excludes all rivals.</p>",

    "22": "<p>The crowd's attack, the magistrates' order to be stripped and beaten — the Passion pattern is being re-enacted in Paul's body. The stripping (cf. Jesus stripped before the soldiers, Matt 27:28), the beating, the imprisonment: Paul's apostolic suffering participates in Christ's own. 2 Cor 1:5 — 'as we share abundantly in Christ's sufferings, so through Christ we share abundantly in comfort too' — is the theological commentary on this scene. Paul's body bears the marks of Jesus (Gal 6:17, <em>ta stigmata tou Iēsou</em>), the physical record of apostolic conformity to the cross.</p>",

    "23": "<p>'After they had been severely flogged, they were thrown into prison, and the jailer was commanded to guard them carefully.' The progressive intensification — public humiliation, flogging, maximum-security imprisonment — reaches its lowest point before the midnight reversal. Christologically, this is the pattern of the Passion: the crucifixion reaches its lowest point of apparent defeat before the resurrection reverses everything. Paul and Silas at midnight are, in miniature, the church at the moment before Easter — imprisoned, beaten, but about to experience the Lord's intervention.</p>",

    "24": "<p>The inner cell and the stocks — the most secure possible confinement — are the human attempt to extinguish the Spirit of Jesus. But the divine answer to maximum security is an earthquake that opens every door. Christologically, the stocks that bind Paul and Silas are images of the tomb that bound Jesus: 'you cannot keep him' (Acts 2:24, 'it was impossible for death to keep its hold on him'). Every human attempt to restrain the gospel's advance meets the same inexorable divine response: the doors open, the chains fall, the mission continues.</p>",

    "25": "<p>Paul and Silas praying and singing hymns to God at midnight is one of the most striking images in Acts. The Christological resonance: 'singing hymns to God' (<em>hymnounta ton theon</em>) in the middle of the night, in the depths of prison, beaten and bound — this is the praise of those who know that suffering cannot separate them from Christ (Rom 8:35-39). The other prisoners listen: the gospel in the prison is not proclamation but worship, and the worship itself is witness. Joy in suffering is a supernatural sign that the one imprisoned is not the prisoner but the kingdom he carries.</p>",

    "26": "<p>The earthquake that opens every door is the Lord's answer to midnight worship. The Christological pattern: as the stone was rolled away from Jesus's tomb (Matt 28:2 — 'there was a violent earthquake, for an angel of the Lord came down from heaven and, going to the tomb, rolled back the stone'), so the prison doors are opened for those who participate in Christ's sufferings. The earthquake is not incidental but theological — divine confirmation that the risen Lord who overcame the sealed tomb can overcome any sealed prison.</p>",

    "27": "<p>The jailer's near-suicide — drawing his sword, assuming prisoners had escaped — reflects Roman military law (a guard who lost prisoners faced execution). His despair is the despair of one who has nothing to live for; it will be reversed by 'believe in the Lord Jesus, and you will be saved' (v31). The Christological trajectory of the whole scene: from maximum security (v24) to maximum despair (v27) to maximum salvation (v31) — the gospel meets human beings at their lowest point and offers a life the world cannot give or take away.</p>",

    "28": "<p>Paul's cry — 'we are all here!' — prevents the jailer's death. The apostle who has been beaten and imprisoned shows more concern for his captor's life than for his own freedom. This is the Christological ethic in action: 'love your enemies, do good to those who hate you' (Luke 6:27) and 'do not repay evil with evil' (Rom 12:17). Paul's refusal to escape when he could have — and his active intervention to prevent harm to the jailer — is the incarnate form of the gospel he will proclaim in v31.</p>",

    "29": "<p>The jailer 'called for lights, rushed in, and fell trembling before Paul and Silas.' His trembling is the fear of a man confronted with something he cannot explain — the divine reversal that left all prisoners present despite open doors. <em>Entromos genomenos</em> (trembling/terrified) is the language of theophanic encounter (cf. Acts 7:32 — Moses trembled at the burning bush; Heb 12:21 — Moses trembled at Sinai). The jailer falls before Paul and Silas not as before deities but as before men who carry the presence of the Most High God (v17) — and whose God has just demonstrated his power.</p>",

    "30": "<p>A direct revelation: 'Sirs, what must I do to be saved?' (<em>Kyrioi, ti me dei poiein hina sōthō</em>) — the central question of Acts and of Paul's entire gospel. The same question that structures the inquiry at Pentecost (2:37, 'what shall we do?') is here asked in its fully personal form. The jailer's question is not theological curiosity but existential desperation — he has just been about to die. The Christological answer (v31) will be the simplest possible: not 'do this and this and this' but 'believe in the Lord Jesus.' The gospel reduces the human condition's deepest question to a single act of trust in a specific person.</p>",

    "31": "<p>A direct revelation: 'Believe in the Lord Jesus, and you will be saved — you and your household.' The simplicity of this gospel proclamation is its Christological precision: the single act required is <em>pisteuō epi ton Kyrion Iēsoun</em> — trusting upon the Lord Jesus. The full name and title matter: 'Lord' (<em>Kyrios</em>) is the LXX divine name applied to the risen Christ; 'Jesus' is the historical name of the man who died and rose. Salvation is not the acceptance of a doctrine but trust in a specific person who is both Lord and human. The household inclusion anticipates v33 — the whole family unit responds to the gospel through the one who believed first.</p>",

    "32": "<p>'Then they spoke the word of the Lord to him and to all the others in his house.' The 'word of the Lord' that follows 'believe in the Lord Jesus' is the Christological content of that belief: who Jesus is, what he did, what his resurrection means, and what it means to live as one who belongs to him. Baptism without instruction, and instruction without baptism, are both incomplete; the apostolic pattern moves from proclamation to faith to baptism to community formation. The jailer's whole household is catechized before dawn.</p>",

    "33": "<p>The jailer takes Paul and Silas, washes their wounds, and then is baptized — all at that hour of the night. The sequence is telling: care for the wounded precedes the baptism. The Christological community does not separate spiritual incorporation from physical care; the one who washes the wounds of those his city beat is already practicing the love that baptism will ratify. 'Immediately he and all his household were baptized' — household baptism in Acts is consistently rapid, reflecting the first generation's understanding that the Spirit comes to those who believe and that baptism is the boundary marker of that belief.</p>",

    "34": "<p>The jailer set a meal before them and was 'filled with joy because he had come to believe in God' — the messianic joy that marks every genuine conversion in Acts (8:8; 8:39; 13:52; 16:34). The meal is simultaneously hospitality (he feeds the men whose chains he had fastened) and table fellowship (the shared meal that anticipates the Lord's Supper). The Christological household — the jailer, his family, and the apostles — eats together at midnight in the praetorium, the Roman prison, as an image of the eschatological banquet (Rev 19:9 — 'blessed are those who are invited to the wedding supper of the Lamb').</p>",

    "35": "<p>The magistrates' morning order to release Paul and Silas — sent before they knew about Paul's Roman citizenship — shows the human system processing the night's events according to its own logic: the disturbance is past, release the troublemakers with a warning. But Paul has a different accounting of what happened, and he will use his legal standing to make a theological point about the gospel's innocence (v37). The Christological community does not flee persecution silently; Paul will require a public acknowledgment of the wrong done to Christ's servants.</p>",

    "36": "<p>The jailer's message — 'the magistrates have ordered that you and Silas be released; now you can leave, go in peace' — is offered in good faith by a man who has become a believer overnight. His 'go in peace' is the blessing of the newly converted, which is both appropriate and insufficient for Paul's purpose. The Christological community has a claim on justice, not merely on charitable release; Paul's insistence on proper procedure (v37) will protect future believers in Philippi who will also need Roman law to function as a safeguard.</p>",

    "37": "<p>Paul's invocation of Roman citizenship — 'they beat us publicly without a trial, even though we are Roman citizens, and threw us into prison' — is both a personal grievance and a strategic deployment of Roman law for the gospel's protection. The Christological principle: the church uses whatever legitimate institutional protections are available to it. Jesus told his disciples to be 'wise as serpents' (Matt 10:16); Paul's knowledge of his rights, and his willingness to assert them, serves the mission rather than mere self-interest. A public retraction protects the Philippian church from being classified as a movement that Roman law has condemned.</p>",

    "38": "<p>The officers' report of Paul's Roman citizenship produces fear (<em>ephobēthēsan</em>) in the magistrates. Fear of institutional accountability reverses the power dynamic: the men who ordered the flogging are now in legal jeopardy. The Christological irony is consistent throughout Acts: the forces of civic power that seek to suppress the gospel repeatedly find themselves on the wrong side of the very laws they administer. Roman law, in Acts, functions as one of the mechanisms by which the risen Christ protects his witnesses from being silenced before the mission is complete.</p>",

    "39": "<p>The magistrates' personal apology — they came, appeased Paul and Silas, and escorted them out — is the civic establishment's acknowledgment that the gospel representatives have been wronged. The word <em>parekalesan</em> (they appeased/entreated) is the same root as <em>paraklēsis</em> (comfort/advocacy) — the magistrates are forced into the posture of supplicants before the men they had beaten. The Christological reversal: those who suffer for the name are vindicated by the structures of human justice, even when those structures previously served as instruments of injustice.</p>",

    "40": "<p>Paul and Silas return to Lydia's house — the home that received the gospel at the city's edge is now the home to which the gospel's beaten witnesses return after its most dramatic confirmation. 'They met with the brothers and sisters and encouraged them, and then they left.' The <em>paraklēsis</em> (encouragement) given to the community before departure is Christ's own strengthening of his body through the apostolic word. The Philippian church — Lydia's household, the jailer's household, and those gathered with them — receives the apostolic blessing before Paul moves on. This community will later receive one of Paul's most affectionate letters (Phil 4:1, 'my joy and my crown').</p>"
  },

  "17": {
    "1": "<p>The journey from Philippi through Amphipolis and Apollonia to Thessalonica follows the Via Egnatia — the major Roman road across Macedonia. Paul and his companions travel the empire's infrastructure, using Roman roads to carry the gospel of a different king. Thessalonica, as the capital of Macedonia and a major harbor city, has a Jewish synagogue — Paul's consistent first point of contact. The Christological logic of the synagogue-first approach: the Scriptures that point to Christ are already there, and the community already knows the God whose Son is now being proclaimed.</p>",

    "2": "<p>'As was his custom, Paul went into the synagogue, and on three Sabbath days he reasoned with them from the Scriptures.' Paul's synagogue method — reasoning from Scripture (<em>dielexato</em>, engaged in dialectical reasoning) — is the same approach Jesus used in the synagogue at Nazareth (Luke 4:16-21) and the pattern established from the first Pentecost sermon (Peter cited Joel, Ps 16, and Ps 110). The Christological claim rests on the OT itself: the Scriptures are not being abandoned but fulfilled. The three Sabbaths represents sustained engagement — not a single sermon but a three-week argument from the text.</p>",

    "3": "<p>A direct revelation: Paul's Thessalonica proclamation is its own Christological thesis statement — 'explaining and proving that the Messiah had to suffer and rise from the dead; this Jesus I am proclaiming to you is the Messiah.' Three elements: (1) <em>dei pathein</em> — the Messiah's suffering is scripturally necessary (Isa 53; Ps 22; Zech 12:10); (2) <em>anastēnai ek nekrōn</em> — the resurrection completes and vindicates the suffering; (3) identification: the Jesus of history IS the Messiah of Scripture. The argument moves from OT necessity to historical event to Christological conclusion. This is the apostolic hermeneutic in one sentence.</p>",

    "4": "<p>Some were persuaded and joined Paul and Silas — Jews, God-fearing Greeks, and prominent women. The socially diverse composition of the first Thessalonian congregation reflects the gospel's cross-cultural reach. The prominent women (<em>gynaikes hai prōtai ouk oligai</em>) suggest that the Thessalonian church, like the Philippian, drew women of social standing; the letter Paul will write (1 Thess) addresses a community with real depth and roots. The Christological community is not demographically homogeneous but draws from every social stratum into a new solidarity in Christ.</p>",

    "5": "<p>The jealous Jews round up 'bad characters from the market-place' to form a mob — the opposition to the gospel follows the same social pattern as in Antioch (13:50), Iconium (14:2-5), and Lystra (14:19). The ones who cannot defeat Paul's scriptural argument respond with social disruption. The attack on Jason's house — seeking Paul and Silas — echoes the mob at Lot's house in Genesis 19, and the Christological parallel to Jesus's own trials: those who cannot answer the message seek to silence the messenger by force.</p>",

    "6": "<p>'These men who have turned the world upside down have come here too!' — the accusers' charge is the most inadvertent tribute in Acts. <em>Hoi tēn oikoumenēn anastatōsantes</em> — 'those who have turned the inhabited world upside down' — is the description of the gospel's impact on the Roman world by those who oppose it. Christologically, this is accurate: the one who said 'I came not to bring peace but a sword' (Matt 10:34) and whose resurrection overturned the entire world order is present in the mission of his apostles. The gospel does turn the world upside down — or rather, right-side up.</p>",

    "7": "<p>'They are all defying Caesar's decrees, saying that there is another king, Jesus.' The political Christology of the gospel surfaces here with full force: <em>basileus heteros</em>, 'another king.' The risen Christ is proclaimed as universal Lord (Acts 2:36 — 'God has made him both Lord and Christ'), which necessarily places him in competition with every other claim to universal sovereignty, including Caesar's. The charge against Paul here precisely identifies the gospel's political implications: not that the gospel is seditious in Roman civic terms, but that it makes a claim about ultimate authority that relativizes all human claims to that authority.</p>",

    "8": "<p>The crowd and the city officials are thrown into turmoil — not because Paul has committed a crime but because the gospel's Christological claims are genuinely destabilizing to a world ordered around competing human powers. The turmoil is the appropriate response to the announcement that God has appointed 'a man' to judge the world (v31): if that is true, everything about the existing power arrangements is provisional and answerable. The gospel does not merely comfort individuals; it restructures the entire framework of accountability.</p>",

    "9": "<p>Jason posts bond — a legal guarantee of good behavior — and is released. The use of bond money to manage religious disruption is a pragmatic Roman solution that treats the gospel as a social problem to be managed rather than a claim to be evaluated. Christologically, the Thessalonian church is born under political pressure and financial constraint — conditions that will shape the community's experience and their reception of Paul's letters (1 Thess 2:14 — 'you suffered from your own people the same things those churches suffered from the Jews in Judea').</p>",

    "10": "<p>The believers send Paul and Silas away by night to Berea — strategic protection of the apostles by the nascent community. The Bereans have a Jewish synagogue, and Paul goes there first. The night departure (cf. Paul's escape from Damascus by night, 9:25) is the church exercising pastoral wisdom: the mission is not served by Paul's martyrdom at this point in God's plan, and so the community protects its apostle for the mission's continuation. The risen Christ protects his missionaries through the agency of their communities.</p>",

    "11": "<p>The Berean Jews 'received the message with great eagerness and examined the Scriptures every day to see if what Paul said was true.' This is the gold standard of Christological reception: not credulity (accepting whatever the charismatic preacher says) but engaged examination of the Scriptures against the claims being made. <em>Anakrinō</em> (to examine, evaluate) is the same word used for judicial investigation. The Bereans' nobility (<em>eugenesters</em>) is not social status but epistemic virtue: they take the gospel seriously enough to test it by the only standard that matters — the Word of God.</p>",

    "12": "<p>'As a result, many of them believed.' The Christological fruit of Berean Scripture-searching is belief — the same outcome that Pentecost's scriptural proclamation produced (2:41). The gospel does not fear examination; it is confirmed by examination. The prominent Greek women and many Greek men who believed confirm that the gospel is crossing ethnic lines: it is not a Jewish sect but the fulfillment of Israel's Scripture that is open to all who will examine and receive it. The demographic diversity of every Acts congregation is a Christological sign of the Messiah's universal reach.</p>",

    "13": "<p>When the Thessalonian Jews learn of Paul's success in Berea, they come to agitate the crowds there too. The persistence of opposition — travelling from one city to the next to counter Paul's preaching — testifies to the gospel's impact. The same forces that killed the prophets, killed Jesus, killed Stephen, and have been opposing Paul at every stop now follow him between cities. The Christological pattern of opposition is geographically mobile because the gospel is geographically mobile; every place the risen Christ plants his witness, the opposition arrives to contest it.</p>",

    "14": "<p>Paul is sent to the coast while Silas and Timothy remain in Berea. The strategic separation protects the mission: if Paul is the primary target of the Thessalonian opposition, his departure removes the provocation while leaving local workers to continue. The Christological wisdom in mission strategy: not every battle is worth fighting in every place; the risen Christ sends his witnesses as 'sheep among wolves' and commands them to 'be wise as serpents' (Matt 10:16-23). Paul's departure is not flight from the cross but stewardship of his calling.</p>",

    "15": "<p>Those who escort Paul bring him to Athens — one of the most important cities in the ancient world, the philosophical capital of Greek civilization. The instructions for Silas and Timothy to join him as soon as possible (cf. 1 Thess 3:1-2, where Paul's account confirms he was alone in Athens) show Paul's recognition that apostolic teamwork is necessary for the mission's sustainability. Athens awaits — the city of Socrates, Plato, Aristotle, the Stoics, and the Epicureans — and Paul will bring the gospel of the crucified and risen Christ into the heart of Greek philosophical culture.</p>",

    "16": "<p>Paul's distress at Athens's idolatry — 'he was greatly distressed to see that the city was full of idols' (<em>parōxyneto to pneuma autou</em>, 'his spirit was provoked/stirred') — is the emotional register of Christological monotheism encountering polytheistic culture. The <em>paroxysmós</em> of Paul's spirit echoes YHWH's anger at Israel's idolatry (LXX Deut 32:16, 21 — Israel provoked him with their idols). Paul is not merely culturally offended but theologically grieved: the city that produced civilization's greatest intellectual achievements is filling the world with false representations of the God who made it. The Christological response will be the Areopagus speech.</p>",

    "17": "<p>Paul's response to Athens's idolatry is proclamation — in the synagogue with Jews and God-fearing Greeks, and in the <em>agora</em> with anyone he met. The marketplace (<em>agora</em>) was where Socrates famously engaged Athenians in philosophical dialogue. Paul occupies Socrates's space with a different message — not the immortality of the soul but the bodily resurrection of Jesus Christ. The Christological content in the marketplace produces the response that every genuine gospel proclamation receives: some mock, some want to hear more, some believe.</p>",

    "18": "<p>Epicurean and Stoic philosophers debate Paul. The Epicureans denied divine providence and held that death ends existence (making resurrection inconceivable); the Stoics believed in universal divine reason (<em>logos</em>) but not personal resurrection. Some dismiss Paul as a <em>spermologos</em> ('babbler' — literally 'seed-picker,' a street-scavenger of scraps of learning). Others accuse him of proclaiming 'foreign deities' (<em>xena daimonia</em>) — the charge on which Socrates was condemned. The Christological proclamation of 'Jesus and the resurrection' (<em>Iēsoun kai tēn anastasin</em>) sounds to Greek ears like two foreign gods: 'Jesus' and 'Anastasia' (female personification of Resurrection).</p>",

    "19": "<p>The Areopagus — the ancient council of Athens, meeting on the rocky hill of Ares northwest of the Acropolis — was both a judicial council and a philosophical debating forum. Paul is not formally on trial (no charge is specified) but is invited to explain his new teaching. The Christological significance: the gospel is being brought before the highest forum of Greek intellectual culture. Paul will not adapt the gospel to Greek philosophy but will use Greek philosophical categories to point beyond themselves to the God who raised Jesus from the dead.</p>",

    "20": "<p>The Athenians' request — 'you are bringing some strange things to our ears; we want to know what they mean' — is genuine philosophical inquiry, not mere curiosity. <em>Xenizonta</em> (strange, foreign) is what the gospel always sounds like to those whose categories have not been shaped by Israel's Scriptures: a God who entered history as a specific man, died, and rose again is not deducible from philosophical first principles. The Christological proclamation is always <em>skandalon</em> and <em>mōria</em> (stumbling block and foolishness, 1 Cor 1:23) before it becomes the power of God.</p>",

    "21": "<p>Luke's observation that Athenians and foreigners 'spent their time doing nothing but talking about and listening to the latest ideas' is both realistic social observation and a gentle irony. Athens's reputation for novelty-seeking is documented by Thucydides and Demosthenes. The Christological point: Paul's audience is one that values new ideas, which gives the gospel a hearing — but the same intellectual restlessness that gives it a hearing may prevent the deep commitment that the gospel requires. The seed falls on different soils; Athens will yield some fruit (Dionysius, Damaris, v34) but no letter, no sustained community like Philippi or Thessalonica.</p>",

    "22": "<p>Paul's opening — 'People of Athens, I see that in every way you are very religious' — is the <em>captatio benevolentiae</em> that opens an argument by acknowledging what the audience already knows about itself. But unlike Tertullus's flattery (24:2-3), Paul's observation is genuine: Athenian religiosity is the human longing that the gospel answers. The Christological apologia begins not with condemnation of idolatry but with recognition of the genuine seeking behind it. This is the incarnational approach: 'I became as a Greek to win Greeks' (1 Cor 9:21) — starting where the audience is, not where Paul would like them to be.</p>",

    "23": "<p>The altar to the Unknown God (<em>Agnōstō Theō</em>) is Paul's interpretive key. Pausanias and Philostratus confirm that such altars existed in Athens. Paul does not claim to introduce a new god but to identify the already-worshipped Unknown One: 'what you worship as unknown I am going to proclaim to you.' The Christological hermeneutic: every genuine human seeking of God is seeking — without knowing it — the God who revealed himself in Jesus Christ. The Unknown God is not a generic deity but the specific Creator who sent his Son. Paul transforms the altar's inscription from confession of ignorance into an invitation to knowledge.</p>",

    "24": "<p>'The God who made the world and everything in it is the Lord of heaven and earth and does not live in temples built by human hands.' The Creator God (<em>ho theos ho poiēsas ton kosmon</em>) = YHWH, identified by his creative act. 'Does not live in temples built by human hands' (<em>cheiropoiētois naois</em>) — the same word <em>cheiropoiētos</em> Stephen used (7:48, citing Isa 66:1-2) to challenge the Jerusalem temple's claim. The Christological argument moves from creation (the Creator transcends the created order, including temples) toward the incarnation: the God who does not dwell in temples nonetheless chose to dwell in the flesh of Jesus Christ (John 1:14).</p>",

    "25": "<p>'He is not served by human hands, as if he needed anything. Rather, he himself gives everyone life and breath and everything.' The self-sufficiency of God and the radical dependency of all creation is the foundation of the Christological argument: the God who gives life to all (including life to the dead, in resurrection) does not need human worship to sustain himself — he worships receive nothing by their worship that God needed. The Christological point: the incarnation is pure gift, not need. The God who became flesh in Jesus Christ did so out of love, not lack.</p>",

    "26": "<p>'From one man (<em>ex henos</em>) he made all the nations.' The one man is Adam — the whole human race shares a common origin and thus a common dignity and a common accountability before God. The Christological background: Paul's Adam Christology (Rom 5:12-21; 1 Cor 15:21-22, 45-49) is implicit here — the one Adam through whom sin came has a counterpart in the one Christ through whom salvation comes. God's marking out 'appointed times and the boundaries of their lands' is Ps 74:17 and Deut 32:8 LXX ('God fixed the boundaries of the peoples according to the number of the sons of God') — the Gentiles' existence within divinely appointed limits is part of the plan leading to the gospel's arrival.</p>",

    "27": "<p>'God did this so that they would seek him and perhaps reach out for him and find him, though he is not far from each one of us.' The entire created order — including the ordering of nations and the passing of times — is designed to produce human seeking after God. The Christological gospel does not undercut natural theology; it completes it. Every genuine human seeking of the divine is seeking the God who revealed himself definitively in the man Jesus Christ. 'He is not far from each one of us' prepares for the gospel's announcement that he came near — in the flesh, in the Word made dwelling (John 1:14).</p>",

    "28": "<p>'For in him we live and move and have our being.' Paul cites Epimenides (or a similar source) and Aratus (<em>Phaenomena</em> 5: 'for we are his offspring') — Greek poets who expressed a intuition of divine immanence and human derivation from the divine. The Christological appropriation: the God whom the poets dimly perceived as the source of human existence is the same God who sent his Son to confirm and restore that relationship. The poetic intuitions of human God-seeking are genuine, though incomplete: they point toward the one in whom those intuitions become personal knowledge through the resurrection.</p>",

    "29": "<p>'Since we are God's offspring, we should not think that the divine being is like gold or silver or stone — an image made by human design and skill.' The argument from the poets now grounds the rejection of idolatry: if we are God's offspring, we cannot be greater than our source; if we cannot be made of gold and silver, our source cannot be. The Christological implication: the divine being has a form — but not gold or silver or stone. The form of the divine is revealed in the human form of Jesus Christ (Phil 2:6-7, 'who, being in very nature God, took on the very nature of a servant, being made in human likeness').</p>",

    "30": "<p>'In the past God overlooked such ignorance, but now he commands all people everywhere to repent.' The eschatological turn in Paul's argument is the hinge between natural theology and the gospel. 'The past' (<em>tous chronous tēs agnoias</em>, the times of ignorance) is the era before the resurrection; 'now' is the new era inaugurated by the resurrection. The universal command to repent follows from the universal lordship of the risen Christ: if God has appointed a specific man to judge the world, then all people must respond to that specific man. The Christological claim is universal in scope — not 'those who happen to hear the gospel' but 'all people everywhere.'</p>",

    "32": "<p>When they heard about the resurrection of the dead, some sneered — the bodily resurrection is the irreducible <em>skandalon</em> of the gospel for Greek philosophy. Plato's <em>Phaedo</em> had argued for the immortality of the soul precisely by arguing that the body is a prison from which death liberates the soul; bodily resurrection would be the soul's reimrisonment, not its liberation. The Christological claim that the <em>body</em> is raised — the same body that died, transformed but continuous — was not merely implausible to Greek ears but philosophically offensive. Others said 'we want to hear you again on this' — the polite deferral of those intrigued but not yet committed.</p>",

    "33": "<p>Paul left the Areopagus — his shortest stay in any city, his only recorded departure without either a Jewish plot against him or a command from the Spirit. Athens receives the least church-planting of any city in Acts; there is no letter to the Athenians, no returning visit recorded. The Christological humility: even the most sophisticated proclamation of the gospel meets resistance, and the gospel does not coerce. Paul plants the seed ('some people became followers of Paul and believed,' v34) and moves on. The harvest at Athens will be small; the harvest at Corinth (ch18) will be large. The risen Christ distributes his vineyard's fruit according to his own wisdom.</p>",

    "34": "<p>Dionysius the Areopagite — a member of the council that had heard Paul — and a woman named Damaris, and others with them, believed. The tradition of the church identified Dionysius as the first bishop of Athens; Damaris's prominence in Luke's record suggests she was a person of some social standing (unusual to name women unless significant). The Christological fruit of the Areopagus speech is small but specific: a member of Athens's highest council and a named woman. The gospel does not judge its fruitfulness by the size of the immediate harvest; it plants in every soil, and the risen Christ determines what grows.</p>"
  }
}

